etymologies: mid 19th century; earliest use found in John William Draper (1811–1882), chemist and historian. From the name of Tithonus (classical Latin Tithōnus, ancient Greek Τῑθωνός; in classical mythology, husband of Aurora (Eos), who was granted immortality but not eternal youth) + -ic, so called with allusion to the fact that the visible effect of such rays on photographic paper fades over time

definitions: In the terminology of John William Draper: designating the largely invisible light rays or components of light which cause chemical effects on photographic films, etc.; of or relating to such light (now recognized to be chiefly ultraviolet) or its effects. Compare "actinic", chemical ray.
